Yelp Review-2¶

-Submitted By: Nibhrat, Raunak, Peter

Abstract¶

Yelp reviews shared by service users for businesses are valuable for both business owners and prospective customers. The reviews consists of text description, star ratings, reviewer’s information etc. People can also vote on user reviews if they find it useful, funny or cool. The aim of our project is to predict user ratings and sentiments using the enormous review data released by Yelp. Here, we plan to conduct a sentiment analysis of the text description of reviews received for businesses in Charlotte. The idea is to find attributes that result in high ratings and thus suggest improvements in certain services in order to attract more customers. Some of the questions we will be interested in includes; how well we can guess a review's rating from its text alone? What are the most common positive and negative words used in our reviews? Can we extract tips from reviews?

Preparation¶

The user review data has been publicly released by Yelp for dataset challenge (https://www.yelp.com/dataset_challenge). The released data consists of 2.7M reviews and 649K tips by 687K users for 86K businesses. However, to simplify our approach, we have only considered review data of Charlotte City. We used 3 major categories of data namely; Business, Review and User. These broad categories consists of attributes of similar class, the details of which were listed in the previous report. The final variables used for the analysis are discussed in detail whenever they appear or are added.

The review data is a complex dataset across multiple dimensions. The attributes we have used are mostly those which have at least 70% data present and thus are statistically significant. The only feature that is not allowed for missing values is the business ID. The decision to remove such rows were taken for the following reasons:

  1. They constitute of less than 1% of total restaurants and are statistically insignificant.
  2. There is no other way that these business ID’s can be recovered thus making the merging process practically impossible.

For the User's dataset, we have classified users based on clustering algorithms and thus have reduced the features of that dataset to 1. We have also used PCA on the clusters to have a better distinction among them. Thus in this dataset, we finally have 10 clusters to classify the type of users and represent their attributes. The clustering procedure used is K-Means.

For the Reviews Dataset, we have used sentiment analysis and Natural Language Processing methods to quantify the sentiments in the text reviews. Each review is processed in an Analyzer which compares words from existing dictionaries of sentiments and is assigned probabilities in 3 categories, namely: Negative, Neutral and Positive. These three probabilities are further used as features averaged for each business and used as features. The Final dataset is merged on Business ID for Business, Sentiment and Users Cluster Data.

Task to solve¶

In this second part of the project here our focus is on to predict the future of the business and classify if they are likely to go out of business in the coming quarter. These results can further be used in discovering factors that lead to failures and thus help businesses to improve upon their existing revenues. Also, if required, a cost analysis can be performed to test the implication, for example; the cost associated with misclassifying a potential shutdown of the business or misclassifying a popular & growing restaurant can be compared.

Metrics used for evaluation:¶

Considering the Categorical nature of most features and binary classification of the restaurant status, we have used 3 main metrics for evaluation namely: Precision, F-1 and Recall. Precision: This metric has been particularly used to measure the inaccuracy in detecting the business that are expected to shut down but are predicted as open. This is important considering the risk/cost associated with such a misclassification. It is better to predict low risk as high risk business than to misclassify the high risk as low risk. Recall: This metric is important to determine the robustness of our model. It depicts the number of Negative samples that are predicted as Negatives. This metric is important to not miss any of the high risk cases. F1 Score: It is the harmonic mean of Precision and Recall and thus weights both of the measures for optimization.

Cross Validation:¶

We used Walk forward approach. It is appropriate considering the time series nature of our analysis. We used the first 2 years to build the initial model and incremented the time quarterly to build and test subsequent models. A schematic presentation of this approach is given below: This is realiistic in approach because we have considered that a 4 month period is a sufficient time for a business to have depreciation in revenues or have similar excuse and thus topple towards shut down. Also, being a time series analysis, we will use continuous training and testing sets across time when the algorithm is deployed.

neighborhoods_1 = list()
neighborhoods_2 = list()
for item in food_charlotte_business.neighborhoods:
    ngh = item.strip('[]')
    ngh = ngh.strip().split(',')
    if (len(ngh) == 1) and ngh[0] != "":
        #print ("Only one neighborhood")
        neighborhoods_1.append(ngh[0].strip("'"))
        neighborhoods_2.append(np.nan)
    elif (len(ngh) == 2):
        #print ("Two neighboorhoods")
        neighborhoods_1.append(ngh[0].strip("'"))
        neighborhoods_2.append(ngh[1].strip("'"))
    else:
        #print ("No Neighborhood")
        neighborhoods_1.append(np.nan)
        neighborhoods_2.append(np.nan)

Sentiment analysis using NLTK¶

We have used Natural Language Processing methods for sentiment analysis of reviews. The NLTK has predefined libraries which have weight defined for positive, negative and nuetral keywords. Each word in the sentence is processed and the review is assigned collective probabilities for Positive Negative and Nuetral Class.

In [12]:
%%time
sid = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()
def sentimentAnalysis(text):
#     ss = TextBlob(text).correct()
    ss = sid.polarity_scores(text)
    return (ss)
    
if __name__ == '__main__':
    num_cores = multiprocessing.cpu_count()
    results = Parallel(n_jobs = -1,backend = 'threading')(delayed(sentimentAnalysis)(sentence) for sentence in charlotte.text)

%%time
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

scl = StandardScaler()
X = scl.fit_transform(user_cluster)

total=0
output=np.array(range(1,50))

for i in range(1,50):
    total=0
    clustercount=i
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=clustercount)
    tempfit=kmeans.fit(X)
    centers=tempfit.cluster_centers_
    for j in range(0,len(centers)):
        testcenter=centers[j]
        points=X[tempfit.labels_==j]
        total+=np.sum(np.linalg.norm(points-testcenter)**2)
    output[i-1]=total
    
plt.plot(range(1,50),output)

# this function definition just formats the weights into readable strings
# you can skip it without loss of generality to the Data Science content
def get_feature_names_from_weights(weights, names):
    tmp_array = []
    for comp in weights:
        tmp_string = ''
        for fidx,f in enumerate(names):
            if fidx>0 and comp[fidx]>=0:
                tmp_string+='+'
            tmp_string += '%.2f*%s ' % (comp[fidx],f[:-5])
        tmp_array.append(tmp_string)
    return tmp_array

Feature Engineering¶

The sentiments are averaged for each business. Then the data is devided into quarters of each year except the initial 2 years which are used for training. The model is tested for each of the nect quarter by training it on all previous time available. The clusters created for representing types of users and the sentiments are collectively used with other attributes in the business data for building the model. The features created for this time series analysis is below:

In [22]:
# http://stackoverflow.com/questions/7015587/python-difference-of-2-datetimes-in-months
def monthdelta(d1, d2):
    delta = 0
    while True:
        mdays = monthrange(d1.year, d1.month)[1]
        d1 += timedelta(days=mdays)
        if d1 <= d2:
            delta += 1
        else:
            break
    return delta
In [23]:
%%time
df = []
start_date = charlotte.date.min()
last_date = charlotte.date.max()
# month_period = monthdelta(start_date,last_date)
date_range = pd.date_range(start_date,last_date,freq='3M')
num = 0
for business_id in charlotte.business_id.unique():
    b_data = charlotte[charlotte.business_id == business_id]
    d1 = start_date
    flag = 0
    for d in date_range[1:]:
        # subset month data
        sub = (b_data.date>=d1)&(b_data.date<d)
        temp = b_data.loc[sub]
        if temp.empty == False:
            # For the first month
            if d1 == start_date:
                users = temp.user_id.unique()
                unique_users_count = len(users)
            else:
                unique_users = [u for u in temp['user_id'] if u not in users.tolist()] # Get unique users
                users = np.append(users,unique_users) # Add unique users to existing users
                unique_users_count = len(unique_users) # Total unique users for the month
                
            clusters = temp.loc[temp['user_id'].isin(users)].cluster_label.value_counts()
            review_count = temp.review_id.count() # Total reviews
            max_rating = temp.review_rating.max() # Max review rating
            min_rating = temp.review_rating.min() # Min Review rating
            avg_rating = temp['review_rating'].mean() # Mean review rating
            review_count_useful = temp['votes.useful'].count() # Useful reviews
            review_count_cool = temp['votes.cool'].count() # Cool reviews
            review_count_funny = temp['votes.funny'].count() # Funny reviews
            active_period = 1 # Active month
            no_months_first_review = monthdelta(start_date,d)
            no_months_last_review = 0 # No of months since the last review
            avg_pos = temp['pos'].mean()
            avg_neg = temp['neg'].mean()
            avg_neutral = temp['neutral'].mean()
            review_d = d 
            flag = 1
        elif (temp.empty==True and flag == 0):
            num+=1
            continue
        else:
            active_period = 0
            no_months_last_review = monthdelta(review_d,d)
            no_months_first_review = monthdelta(start_date,d)

        # add to data frame
        df.append([business_id,d,review_count,max_rating,min_rating,avg_rating,review_count_useful,
                   review_count_cool,review_count_funny,unique_users_count,active_period,no_months_last_review,clusters])
        d1 = d # Assign 'start date' as the current month
        num+=1
        sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d' % num)
        sys.stderr.flush()

Classification¶

As discussed before; a time series analysis has been performed and businesses are classified in the High risk(Close) and no risk category(Open). Various algorithms used are shown below:

In [4]:
from dateutil.relativedelta import relativedelta
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn import metrics as mt

def build_model(final_df,clf_obj):
    period_relative = relativedelta(months = 3)
    period = pd.to_datetime(final_df.Period_EndDate.unique()).sort_values()
    sub_period = period[8:]
    metrics = []
    clf = []
    num = 0
    
    for date in sub_period:
        train = final_df[final_df.Period_EndDate <= date]
        train = train.drop('Period_EndDate',axis = 1)
        
        test = final_df[final_df.Period_EndDate == (date+period_relative)]
        test = test.drop('Period_EndDate',axis=1)
        
        if test.empty == False:
            X_train = train.drop('open',axis=1,inplace=False).values
            Y_train = train['open'].values
            
            X_test = test.drop('open',axis=1,inplace=False).values
            Y_test = test['open'].values
            
            clf_obj.fit(X_train,Y_train)
            Y_hat = clf_obj.predict(X_test)
            
            #Compute relevant metrics
            acc = mt.accuracy_score(Y_test,Y_hat)
            cm_metrics = mt.precision_recall_fscore_support(Y_test,Y_hat,average = 'binary',pos_label = 0)
            class_count = np.unique(Y_test,return_counts = True)[1]
            class_ratio = class_count[0]/class_count[1]
            metrics.append([date,acc,len(X_train),len(X_test),cm_metrics[0],cm_metrics[1],
                           cm_metrics[2],class_ratio])
            clf.append(clf_obj)
        else:
            continue
        
        num+=1
        sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d' %num)
        sys.stderr.flush()
        
    return(clf,metrics)
In [5]:
def plot_metrics(metrics):
    metrics = metrics.drop(['Train_Data_Size','Test_Data_Size'],axis = 1,inplace = False)
    metrics['Date'] = metrics['Date'].dt.date
    metrics_df = pd.melt(metrics,id_vars=['Date','reg_param'],value_vars=['Accuracy','Precision',
                                                                          'Recall','F1_Score','Class_Ratio'],
                        var_name = 'Name',value_name='Metrics')
    
    grouped = metrics_df.groupby('reg_param')
    nrows = int(len(grouped.groups)/2)
    sns.set_style("whitegrid")

    fig,ax = plt.subplots(nrows,2,figsize = (20,20))
    for (ind,group),ax in zip(grouped,ax.flat):
        ax.set_frame_on(False)
        ax.set_title(("Regularization="+str(ind)),fontsize=20)
        ax.set_xlabel("Test Period",fontsize = 14)
        ax.set_ylabel("Metric Value",fontsize =14)
        g = sns.pointplot(data = group,x="Date",y = "Metrics",hue = "Name",ax=ax,legend=False)
        g.set(ylim=(0.5,1))
        xticks = [item.get_text() for item in ax.get_xticklabels()]
        ax.set_xticklabels(labels = xticks,rotation = 90)
        g.legend_.remove()
        plt.tight_layout()
    plt.legend()

Logistic Regression¶

For the llogistic regression, we have varied the regularization parameter (from 0.001 to 1000 with multiplicative increments of 10) and plotted various parameters to select the best one.

In [98]:
%%time

## Logistic Regression
reg_param = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000]
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame()

for c in reg_param:
    clf_lr = LogisticRegression(penalty = 'l2',C = c,class_weight = 'balanced',warm_start = True,
                                n_jobs = -1,solver = 'lbfgs')
    clf_perf = build_model(final_df,clf_lr)
    metrics = clf_perf[1]
    metrics = pd.DataFrame(metrics,columns = ['Date','Accuracy','Train_Data_Size','Test_Data_Size',
                                              'Precision','Recall','F1_Score','Class_Ratio'])
    metrics['reg_param'] = c
#     weights = np.array(clf_perf[0].coef_[0])
    # weights = np.array(clf_perf[2])
    # plot_weight(weights)
    metrics_df = pd.concat((metrics_df,metrics))

SVM¶

Support Vector Machines is another algorithm that we have tried. Tuning the Regularization parameter and gamma have produced results of high precision. The summary of the metric measures is given below.

In [17]:
%%time
## SVM
# Linear SVM
reg_param = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000]
gamma = [0.00001,0.0001,0.01,0.1,1,10]

def rbfSVM(c,g):
    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame()
    clf_rbfSVM = SVC(kernel = 'rbf',C=c,gamma = g,class_weight = 'balanced',random_state = 1)
    clf_perf = build_model(final_df,clf_rbfSVM)
    metrics = clf_perf[1]
    metrics = pd.DataFrame(metrics,columns = ['Date','Accuracy','Train_Data_Size','Test_Data_Size',
                                              'Precision','Recall','F1_Score','Class_Ratio'])
    metrics['reg_param'] = c
    metrics['gamma'] = g
    return (metrics)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    num_cores = multiprocessing.cpu_count()
    metrics_df = Parallel(n_jobs = -1,backend = 'threading')(delayed(rbfSVM)(c,g) for c,g in zip(reg_param,gamma))

Multi-layer Perceptron¶

For the multi layer perceptron algorithm used below, we have varied the number of layers in the perceptron as 10, 50 and 100. We also varied the activation function and found the logistic fuction to be more precise. The results of the various metric measures are plotted below.

In [12]:
## MLP
from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame()
layer_size = [(10,),(50,),(10,10),(50,50),(100,100),(10,10,10),(50,50,50)]
for layer in layer_size:
    clf_mlp = MLPClassifier(hidden_layer_sizes=layer,warm_start=True,activation = 'logistic',random_state=1)
    clf_perf = build_model(final_df,clf_mlp)
    metrics = clf_perf[1]
    metrics = pd.DataFrame(metrics,columns = ['Date','Accuracy','Train_Data_Size','Test_Data_Size',
                                          'Precision','Recall','F1_Score','Class_Ratio'])
#     metrics['reg_param'] = np.sum(list(layer))
    metrics['reg_param'] = str(layer)
    metrics_df = pd.concat((metrics_df,metrics))

Random Forest¶

We have also employed Random Forest. We selected the Bootstrap to be true, selection criteria to be entropy (Gini is not suitable in case of time series analysis here) and varied the number of trees from 10 to 500. The various results for the chosen metrics are shown below:

In [22]:
## Random Forest

n_trees = [10,100,200,500,1000]
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame()
for tree in n_trees:
    clf_rf = rf(n_estimators = tree,criterion='entropy',max_features = 'auto',bootstrap = True,
                n_jobs = -1,class_weight = 'balanced',random_state = 1)
    clf_perf = build_model(final_df,clf_rf)
    metrics = clf_perf[1]
    metrics = pd.DataFrame(metrics,columns = ['Date','Accuracy','Train_Data_Size','Test_Data_Size',
                                          'Precision','Recall','F1_Score','Class_Ratio'])
    metrics['reg_param'] = tree
    metrics_df = pd.concat((metrics_df,metrics))

As clearly seen from the above graphs, the precision is very high. This can be attributed to the overfitting of the model. Also, other parameters like F-1 are also high. Comparison of best performing models¶

The algorithms discussed above are compared and tested statistically after using the optimized tuning parameters. The results of 95% significance of area under ROC is presented later.

In [70]:
metrics_df_svm = pd.read_csv('D:/Yelp/SVM_Metrics.csv')
In [103]:
rf_best = metrics_df_rf[metrics_df_rf.reg_param == 100]
rf_best['clf'] = 'rf'
svm_best = metrics_df_svm[(metrics_df_svm.gamma==0.1) & (metrics_df_svm.reg_param == 1.0)]
svm_best['clf'] = 'svm'
mlp_best = metrics_df_mlp[metrics_df_mlp.reg_param==str((100,100))] 
mlp_best['clf'] = 'mlp'
lr_best = metrics_df_lr[metrics_df_lr.reg_param == 1]
lr_best['clf'] = 'lr'

models_perf = pd.concat([rf_best,svm_best,mlp_best,lr_best])


# models_perf['Date'] = models_perf['Date'].dt.date

Ensemble - Majority Voting¶

The best performing algorithms are combined into an ensemble and Majority Voting is used.

Final Model Analysis¶

In [17]:
def build_model_finalPeriod(final_df,clf_obj):
    period_relative = relativedelta(months = 3)
    period = pd.to_datetime(final_df.Period_EndDate.unique()).sort_values()
    sub_period = period[len(period)-2]
    date = sub_period
    metrics = []
    clf = []
    num = 0
    train = final_df[final_df.Period_EndDate <= date]
    train = train.drop('Period_EndDate',axis = 1)
        
    test = final_df[final_df.Period_EndDate == (date+period_relative)]
    test = test.drop('Period_EndDate',axis=1)
        
    X_train = train.drop('open',axis=1,inplace=False).values
    Y_train = train['open'].values
            
    X_test = test.drop('open',axis=1,inplace=False).values
    Y_test = test['open'].values
            
    clf_obj.fit(X_train,Y_train)
    Y_hat = clf_obj.predict(X_test)
    y_score = clf_obj.predict_proba(X_test)
            
    #Compute relevant metrics
    acc = mt.accuracy_score(Y_test,Y_hat)
    cm = mt.confusion_matrix(Y_test,Y_hat)
    cm_metrics = mt.precision_recall_fscore_support(Y_test,Y_hat,average = 'binary',pos_label = 0)
    class_count = np.unique(Y_test,return_counts = True)[1]
    class_ratio = class_count[0]/class_count[1]
    metrics.append([date,acc,len(X_train),len(X_test),cm_metrics[0],cm_metrics[1],
                    cm_metrics[2],class_ratio])
    clf.append(clf_obj)
        
    num+=1
    sys.stderr.write('\rEpoch: %d' %num)
    sys.stderr.flush()
        
    return(clf,metrics,cm,Y_test,Y_hat, y_score)

ROC Curves¶

In [20]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import label_binarize
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
def plot_roc(clf_obj,y_test,y_score,title):
    roc_auc = dict()
    n_classes = 2
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_score)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    
    plt.figure()
    lw = 2
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange',
             lw=lw, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=lw, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic: '+title)
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

Deployment:¶

Given the high precision and recall, we can assert that the model is quite successfull in predicting a shut-down of a business. The model precision and Recall can be further improved if Yelp releases the exact dates for closure of a business. By the results of our model, we can surely say that businesses will be benefitted and can improve their services to avoid a possible shut-down, which they might not be aware of. For about 90% of the time we are able to predict the shut-down well ahead of time and the high recall in the model suggests that it rarely misses the future of businesses at high risk. If deployed as suggested, this can prove vital in making improvements to increase revenue and avoid risk.
